---
/**
 * About — the person behind Mission Built, plus the project's own
 * mission. Long-form narrative prose. Single column, max-width 720,
 * matching the Reading View's main column for visual continuity.
 *
 * Content lifted from the current missionbuilt.io/about page (in
 * Mike's own voice). Light edits: professional sentence updated to
 * reflect his current GM role at Elastic Security (Nov 2025).
 */
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import TopNav from '../components/TopNav.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="About · Mission Built"
  description="The person behind Mission Built. Mike Nichols. Product leader by trade, powerlifter by obsession, father before all else."
  active="about"
>
  <TopNav active="about" />

  <main class="page">
    {/* ---------- HEADER ---------- */}
    <header class="hero">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1 class="hero-h1">
        Hi, I'm <a
          class="hero-link"
          href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/hmikenichols"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          aria-label="Mike Nichols on LinkedIn"
        >Mike<span class="ext" aria-hidden="true"> ↗</span></a>.
      </h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Product leader by trade. Powerlifter by obsession. Father before all else.
      </p>
    </header>

    <article class="prose">
      {/* ---------- PROFESSIONAL JOURNEY ---------- */}
      <section>
        <h2>Professional Journey</h2>
        <p>
          I'm the General Manager of Elastic Security, leading the global
          organization across product and engineering toward a single mission:
          democratizing security for everyone.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before this role, I was VP of Product Management at Elastic. I led the
          creation of Elastic Security from inception, formed out of the
          acquisition of Endgame. The work united engineering, product, and
          go-to-market behind a single offering, and earned recognition from
          IDC, Forrester, AV-Comparatives, and Gartner across SIEM, analytics,
          and XDR.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before that, I was VP of Product at Endgame. We took on the giants of
          endpoint security: McAfee, CrowdStrike. We didn't try to outspend them.
          We entered with a clear mission: protect high-value targets from
          nation-state level attacks. A small, fierce team rallied behind that
          focus and carved out real ground in a brutally competitive market.
        </p>
        <p class="closer">
          That's the work I'm proudest of. We didn't win on money or brand. We
          had something harder to copy: a clear mission.
        </p>
        <p>
          Between the Army and Endgame, I was an operator. Security analyst and
          shift lead at large SOCs like DHS. That work bathed me in empathy for
          the tireless, thankless effort of those teams. Every product I've
          built since carries that with me.
        </p>
        <p>
          Before any of it, I was an intelligence analyst in the U.S. Army. That
          mindset has never left.
        </p>
        <p>
          I've been in cybersecurity since 2002. Army intel. SOC operations.
          Product leadership. One belief has carried through all of it: we win
          when our users do.
        </p>
        <p>
          Whether I'm mentoring teams or shaping roadmaps, my product philosophy
          is rooted in empathy, mission, and execution. I've never believed in
          building for metrics. I build for outcomes.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- BEYOND WORK ---------- */}
      <section>
        <h2>Beyond Work</h2>
        <p>
          Outside of work, I'm a USAPL-certified powerlifting coach and a
          not-so-serious competitive lifter. My platform may be unofficial, but my PR
          board is sacred.
        </p>
        <p>
          I train in the garage gym I've been obsessively building for years. A
          personal cathedral of steel and sweat. It's where I reset, get stronger, and
          connect with the people I love. The home gym is more than racks and rep
          schemes; it's a space that keeps my body sharp and my mind clearer than any
          meeting ever could.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- FAMILY ---------- */}
      <section>
        <h2>Family</h2>
        <p>
          I'm a proud and lucky dad who learned the meaning of unconditional love the
          moment they arrived. They've taught me more about patience, play, and
          perspective than any product launch ever could.
        </p>
        <p class="closer">
          Here's what you'll get from me, in my work, my writing, or my life:
          honesty, heart, and a little bit of barbell grit. I don't pretend to have
          all the answers, but I show up, give a shit, and do the reps. Every day.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- DIVIDER ---------- */}
      <hr class="section-divider" />

      {/* ---------- ABOUT THE BOOK ---------- */}
      <section>
        <p class="kicker">The Mission Behind MissionBuilt</p>
        <h2>Why this book exists</h2>
        <p>
          MissionBuilt was born from a simple idea: the principles driving successful
          product teams and driven lifters are more alike than they seem. I've spent
          decades in both worlds: tech product management and competitive
          powerlifting. The same core truths show up in each. Consistency, purpose,
          and relentless focus on the mission.
        </p>
        <p>
          This project isn't a manifesto. It's not here to tell you how it must be
          done. It's a personal contribution to the shared pool of knowledge: a new
          lens for understanding the craft of product leadership, seen through the
          eyes of the lifter, the builder, the grinder.
        </p>
        <p>
          Some people learn best from frameworks and acronyms. Others need narrative
          and analogy. MissionBuilt is for the latter. It's product management as
          told through the chalk-dusted hands of someone who's felt the pressure of a
          heavy barbell and a tight roadmap.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- THIS PROJECT EXISTS TO ---------- */}
      <section>
        <h2>This project exists to:</h2>
        <ul class="missions">
          <li>
            Offer a free and open-source book that ties together the rigor of
            product leadership with the discipline of physical training.
          </li>
          <li>
            Present an alternative philosophy, not a prescriptive method.
          </li>
          <li>
            Encourage introspection, empathy, and ownership, especially in a world
            that too often prizes speed over substance.
          </li>
          <li>
            Share what's been learned from years of building: products, teams,
            strength, and character.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="closer">
          Most of all, MissionBuilt exists because you might be like me. Someone who
          cares deeply, grinds daily, and believes that strength (in life, in teams,
          in outcomes) is built, not bought.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- EMBRACING AI ---------- */}
      <section>
        <h2>Embracing AI</h2>
        <p>
          I'm not just okay with using AI. I depend on it. MissionBuilt is a
          product of passion, purpose, and pragmatic tooling. AI is the creative
          amplifier that lets me move faster without burning out. It's how I stay
          honest to the mission while still making time for the kids, the training,
          the team.
        </p>
        <p>
          This open-source book and everything around it were made with human
          experience and machine acceleration. Not to replace craft, but to respect
          time. I believe in spending hours where they matter most: with the users I
          serve, under the bar, or beside the people I love.
        </p>
        <p>
          AI didn't write this for me. But it helped me write it faster and with
          fewer excuses. And I'm proud of that.
        </p>
        <p>
          So no, this isn't a luddite's blog. It's not a shrine to handcrafted
          suffering. It's a modern-day field manual forged by a human lifter,
          builder, and father, built with tools that work.
        </p>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- OPEN THANKS ---------- */}
      <section>
        <h2>Open Thanks</h2>
        <p>
          Mission Built isn't just a book. It's a collaboration across domains,
          disciplines, and even dimensions. An open-source memoir shaped by years
          of lifting, building, and listening, made possible by a growing circle of
          co-authors, contributors, and creative forces.
        </p>
        <p>This project wouldn't exist without:</p>
        <dl class="thanks">
          <div>
            <dt>My team</dt>
            <dd>in product, in security, and across the org, who prove every day that shipping with care is stronger than shipping fast.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>My kids</dt>
            <dd>my constant "why," reminding me what real strength looks like.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>My beyond</dt>
            <dd>for fueling the kind of love and fire that moves worlds.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>Claude &amp; ChatGPT</dt>
            <dd>for showing up every rep and turning late-night thoughts into something worth sharing.</dd>
          </div>
          <div>
            <dt>Every reader, challenger, and builder</dt>
            <dd>who engages, critiques, and adds weight to these ideas.</dd>
          </div>
        </dl>
      </section>

      {/* ---------- FINE PRINT ---------- */}
      <aside class="fine-print" aria-label="Fine print">
        <p class="fp-kicker">Fine print</p>
        <p>
          This site and the book are for thinking and conversation, not medical,
          legal, or financial advice. The powerlifting opinions are mine and not a
          training program. Train smart, listen to your body, hire a coach when it
          counts.
        </p>
      </aside>

      {/* ---------- CLOSER ---------- */}
      <footer class="closer-block">
        <p class="closer-tag">This is just the beginning.</p>
        <p class="closer-credo">Real strength is lifting others.</p>
      </footer>
    </article>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  /* ============ HEADER ============ */
  .hero {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 56px var(--pad-page-x) 28px;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0 0 14px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.24em;
    color: var(--color-blood);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .hero-h1 {
    margin: 0 0 14px;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: clamp(34px, 5vw, 52px);
    line-height: 1.0;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-chalk);
  }
  /* "Mike" in the headline links to LinkedIn — subtle underline that
     lifts to oxblood on hover, mirroring the home page author block. */
  .hero-link {
    color: inherit;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-rule);
    transition: color 120ms ease-out, border-bottom-color 120ms ease-out;
  }
  .hero-link:hover {
    color: var(--color-blood);
    border-bottom-color: var(--color-blood);
  }
  .hero-link .ext {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-left: 4px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.42em;
    color: var(--color-chalk-faint);
    letter-spacing: 0;
    text-transform: none;
    vertical-align: 0.35em;
    transition: color 120ms ease-out;
  }
  .hero-link:hover .ext { color: var(--color-blood); }

  .lede {
    margin: 0;
    max-width: 600px;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 20px;
    line-height: 1.45;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    color: var(--color-chalk-dim);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  /* ============ PROSE ============ */
  .prose {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 36px var(--pad-page-x) 80px;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    color: var(--color-chalk);
  }

  .prose section + section { margin-top: 36px; }
  .prose section:first-of-type { margin-top: 0; }

  .prose h2 {
    margin: 0 0 16px;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 24px;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-chalk);
  }

  .prose .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 6px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    color: var(--color-army);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  .prose p {
    margin: 0 0 18px;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-chalk);
  }
  .prose p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }

  /* "Closer" lines — slightly dimmer or italic emphasis at end of section */
  .prose p.closer {
    margin-top: 22px;
    color: var(--color-chalk);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  /* Section divider between "Me" and "The Book" */
  .section-divider {
    margin: 56px 0;
    border: 0;
    height: 1px;
    background: var(--color-rule);
  }

  /* Mission list */
  .missions {
    list-style: none;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 18px 28px;
  }
  .missions li {
    position: relative;
    padding: 14px 16px 14px 22px;
    background: var(--color-panel);
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-chalk-dim);
  }
  .missions li::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    top: 14px;
    bottom: 14px;
    width: 2px;
    background: var(--color-army);
  }

  /* Open Thanks */
  .thanks {
    margin: 14px 0 0;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
  .thanks > div {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 220px 1fr;
    gap: 18px;
    align-items: baseline;
    padding: 14px 0;
    border-top: 1px dashed var(--color-rule-soft);
  }
  .thanks > div:first-child { border-top: none; }
  .thanks dt {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 15px;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-chalk);
  }
  .thanks dd {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 16px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-chalk-dim);
  }

  /* ============ FINE PRINT ============ */
  .fine-print {
    margin-top: 56px;
    padding: 18px 22px;
    background: var(--color-panel);
  }
  .fine-print .fp-kicker {
    margin: 0 0 6px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    color: var(--color-chalk-faint);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .fine-print p:not(.fp-kicker) {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-chalk-dim);
  }

  /* ============ CLOSER BLOCK ============ */
  .closer-block {
    margin-top: 48px;
    padding: 36px 0 0;
    border-top: var(--border-thin);
    text-align: center;
  }
  .closer-tag {
    margin: 0 0 8px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.24em;
    color: var(--color-chalk-faint);
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }
  .closer-credo {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 24px;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-blood);
  }

  /* ============ Responsive ============ */
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .hero {
      padding: 36px var(--pad-page-x-mobile) 20px;
    }
    .lede { font-size: 17px; }

    .prose {
      padding: 28px var(--pad-page-x-mobile) 60px;
    }
    .prose section + section { margin-top: 28px; }
    .prose h2 { font-size: 22px; }
    .prose p { font-size: 16px; }

    .missions {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 12px;
    }

    .thanks > div {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 4px;
    }

    .section-divider { margin: 40px 0; }

    .closer-block { margin-top: 48px; padding-top: 28px; }
    .closer-credo { font-size: 20px; }
  }
</style>
